  "prompt": "Why is Balsam plant wilt during midday even if the soil is well watered?",
  "response": "Balsam plants (Impatiens walleriana) may wilt during midday due to several reasons, even when the soil is adequately watered:\n\n1. Heat stress\n- High temperatures cause rapid transpiration\n- Plants temporarily wilt to reduce water loss\n- This is a protective mechanism called \"midday depression\"\n\n2. Insufficient root system\n- Young or recently transplanted plants may have underdeveloped roots\n- Limited root network reduces water uptake efficiency\n\n3. Direct sunlight exposure\n- Balsams prefer partial shade\n- Full sun can cause excessive water loss and wilting\n- Leaves droop to minimize sun exposure and reduce transpiration\n\n4. Humidity levels\n- Low humidity increases transpiration rate\n- Plants lose water faster than they can absorb\n\n5. Leaf surface area\n- Large, thin leaves lose water quickly\n- Rapid water loss leads to temporary wilting\n\n6. Potential root problems\n- Root damage\n- Poor drainage\n- Root rot\n- Nematode infections\n\nRecommended solutions:\n- Provide partial shade\n- Mulch to retain soil moisture\n- Ensure proper drainage\n- Water deeply but not excessively\n- Monitor plant health\n\nNormal wilting typically resolves by evening when temperatures decrease.",
